251. Aricia was the first stopping-place after leaving Rome by the Via Appia, cf. Hor. Sat. 1., v. 1 “ Egressum magna me excepit Aricia Roma.” The ‘lake of the valley of Aricia’ Lacus Nemorensis is now called the Lago di Nemi.

253. Hippolytus, whose story is told in the Hippolytus of Euripides, was thrown from his chariot through his horses taking fright, and his body torn in pieces. Aesculapius restored him to life, and Diana placed him in her grove at Aricia. The local name given to him was Virbius. See VI. 661.
